  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects students like me who are navigating the education system without the same support many others have. Growing up in Naples with parents who have vocational diplomas and upper secondary education, I've seen firsthand how the pressure to conform to stereotypes about who 'belongs' in science and technology can make it feel impossible to thrive. When I'm in a classroom or lab, I often feel this weight of expectation—like I'm being judged not for my ability but for my gender or background. As someone who's anxious and tends to overthink, this stress can make me question my own skills, even when I know I'm capable. Stereotype threat is when the fear of confirming a negative stereotype about one's group lowers performance, and in STEM fields, this can be especially harmful because the field is often perceived as 'for' certain groups. The good news is that we absolutely should address it. In my community, I've seen how simple things like mentorship programs, inclusive classroom practices, and open conversations about bias can make a huge difference. For example, when I volunteer with local STEM clubs, I notice how creating safe spaces where everyone feels they belong helps students like me to engage more confidently. Addressing stereotype threat isn't just about fixing a problem—it's about building a future where everyone has the chance to contribute their full potential without fear. It's something we all need to work on, especially as young people who are trying to shape the world we want to live in.",
